@startuml 01_login_workflow_prod
title BookRover — Login Workflow (PROD)\nAll Roles: Admin · Group Leader · Seller (new & returning)

skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true
skinparam roundcorner 8
skinparam defaultFontSize 13

actor       "User\n(Browser)"                       as User
participant "React App\n(CloudFront CDN)"           as FE
participant "Amazon Cognito\n(User Pool)"           as Cognito
participant "API Gateway\n(HTTP API)"               as APIGW
participant "Lambda\n(FastAPI via Mangum)"          as BE
database    "DynamoDB\n(AWS Managed)"               as DB

note over FE, BE
  **PROD environment variables required**

  Frontend (set at build time via Vite):
    VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://<api-id>.execute-api.<region>.amazonaws.com
    VITE_COGNITO_USER_POOL_ID=<user-pool-id>
    VITE_COGNITO_CLIENT_ID=<app-client-id>
    VITE_COGNITO_REGION=<region>

  Backend (Lambda environment variables):
    APP_ENV=prod
    ADMIN_EMAILS=admin@example.com
    BOOKROVER_TABLE_PREFIX=bookrover
    AWS_REGION=<region>
    COGNITO_USER_POOL_ID=<user-pool-id>
    COGNITO_REGION=<region>
    COGNITO_CLIENT_ID=<app-client-id>
    (No AWS credentials needed — Lambda IAM role provides access)

  AWS Infrastructure:
    Cognito User Pool — email sign-in, Email OTP auth flow enabled (ALLOW_USER_AUTH)
    Lambda IAM Role — DynamoDB: GetItem, PutItem, Query, Scan, UpdateItem, DeleteItem
                      on specific table ARNs only (least privilege)
    API Gateway — throttling enabled, CORS restricted to CloudFront origin only
end note

== Step 1 — User initiates login via Cognito ==

User  -> FE : Navigate to /login\nEnter email + click Continue
FE    -> Cognito : InitiateAuth — email OTP request\n(AWS Amplify SDK — signIn with USER_AUTH flow)

note right of Cognito
  Cognito sends a 6-digit one-time code
  to the user's email address.
  No password required — email is
  the identity proof.
end note

Cognito --> User : Email with 6-digit OTP
User  -> FE : Enter OTP
FE    -> Cognito : RespondToAuthChallenge — submit OTP

Cognito --> FE : AuthenticationResult\n{ IdToken (JWT), AccessToken, RefreshToken }

FE    -> FE : Store IdToken in localStorage\n('bookrover_token')\nStore RefreshToken for silent refresh

note right of FE
  The IdToken is a signed JWT (RS256).
  It contains: email, sub (user ID),
  exp (expiry), iss (Cognito issuer URL).
  It is NOT decodable by end users
  to reveal secrets (claims are visible
  but signature cannot be forged).
end note

== Step 2 — Resolve BookRover identity via GET /me ==

FE    -> APIGW : GET /me\nAuthorization: Bearer <CognitoIdToken>
APIGW -> BE    : Forward request (after throttle/CORS check)
BE    -> BE    : Extract Bearer token from Authorization header
BE    -> Cognito : Fetch JWKS (public keys) — cached after first call\n(https://cognito-idp.<region>.amazonaws.com/<pool-id>/.well-known/jwks.json)
BE    -> BE    : Verify JWT signature + expiry + issuer
BE    -> BE    : Extract email from token claims

alt email in ADMIN_EMAILS env var
    BE   --> APIGW : 200 { roles: ["admin"],\n  seller_id: null, group_leader_id: null }
    APIGW -> FE : Forward response
    FE    -> FE : AuthContext.setMe()\nnavigate("/admin")

else email found in group-leaders table
    BE    -> DB : Query group-leaders by email (GSI on email)
    DB   --> BE : GroupLeader record
    BE   --> APIGW : 200 { roles: ["group_leader"],\n  group_leader_id: "uuid", seller_id: null }
    APIGW -> FE : Forward response
    FE    -> FE : AuthContext.setMe()\nnavigate("/dashboard")

else email found in sellers table
    BE    -> DB : Query sellers by email (GSI on email)
    DB   --> BE : Seller record
    BE   --> APIGW : 200 { roles: ["seller"],\n  seller_id: "uuid", group_leader_id: null }
    APIGW -> FE : Forward response
    FE    -> FE : AuthContext.setMe()\nnavigate("/inventory")

else email verified by Cognito but not yet registered
    BE    -> DB : Query group-leaders — no match
    BE    -> DB : Query sellers — no match
    BE   --> APIGW : 200 { roles: [], seller_id: null, group_leader_id: null }
    APIGW -> FE : Forward response
    FE    -> FE : AuthContext.setMe()\nnavigate("/register")
end

== Step 3 — Silent token refresh ==

note over FE, Cognito
  Cognito IdTokens expire (default: 1 hour).
  Before calling any API, the React app checks token expiry.
  If expired, it uses the RefreshToken to get a new IdToken silently —
  no user interaction needed — then retries the API call.
end note

== Step 4 — Logout (any role) ==

User  -> FE : Click Logout
FE    -> Cognito : GlobalSignOut (invalidates all tokens for this user)
FE    -> FE : localStorage.removeItem('bookrover_token')\nAuthContext.setMe(null)\nnavigate("/login")

@enduml
